get an offer, it's 20 bucks. I'm picking someone 
up from point A, I'm dropping them off at point B.  

182
00:16:11,840 --> 00:16:18,880
There's a bit of an excitement angle and I don't 
want to overplay it. Earners, drivers work really,  

183
00:16:18,880 --> 00:16:23,280
really hard to do their job, but I think 
that part of our product, there's a bit of  

184
00:16:23,280 --> 00:16:29,440
an excitement to it. That was a surprise to me.
I will go into a few individual features,  

185
00:16:29,440 --> 00:16:35,600
but even at a more meta level, the thing 
that surprised me the most is we obsess  

186
00:16:35,600 --> 00:16:41,360
about our app and our app is the center of our 
universe, but when a passenger gets in the car,  

187
00:16:41,360 --> 00:16:47,120
the center of the driver's universe is that 
interaction with the passenger. That human touch  

188
00:16:47,120 --> 00:16:52,000
between the driver and the passenger is something 
that we don't talk about in the office enough.  

189
00:16:52,000 --> 00:16:56,880
And if you talk to the driver and when I'm a 
driver, if the passenger is friendly, it lifts my  

190
00:16:56,880 --> 00:17:02,320
mood. If the passenger is grumpy, then I'm unsure 
what to do. If the passenger is rude, which has  

191
00:17:02,320 --> 00:17:09,440
also happened, that can really be demotivating.
I want to share one anecdote with you. This was  

192
00:17:09,440 --> 00:17:15,600
way back almost eight years ago when I started 
driving. This was probably my fifth or sixth trip,  

193
00:17:15,600 --> 00:17:19,840
so I was very, very early in my journey 
of dogfooding. So it was early morning,  

194
00:17:19,840 --> 00:17:25,200
I think it was a Saturday morning maybe about 
7:00 a.m. I was picking someone up, it was a lady,  

195
00:17:25,200 --> 00:17:29,920
I stopped my car on the curbside. She got in, she 
was going to the airport, she was going to San  

196
00:17:29,920 --> 00:17:37,200
Jose airport and she had a suitcase, but she left 
on the curb and she's inside the car and I'm like,  

197
00:17:37,200 --> 00:17:43,120
"What's going on?" And it suddenly dawned on me 
that she's expecting me to get out of my car,  

198
00:17:43,120 --> 00:17:47,120
grab her suitcase, open the trunk, 
and put the suitcase in the car,  

199
00:17:47,120 --> 00:17:54,320
but she didn't say anything. And then I suddenly 
realized that there is an expectation of me as  

200
00:17:54,320 --> 00:17:59,680
the driver doing that part of the job as well.
And since I was very early in my journey, I had  

201
00:17:59,680 --> 00:18:05,680
not internalized that and the kind of emotions 
that ran through me at that time just explained to  

202
00:18:05,680 --> 00:18:10,160
me, "Hey, what does a driver actually go through?" 
That was a somber ride for me. That was a somber  

203
00:18:10,160 --> 00:18:15,760
day for me. And since that day, I have not 
forgotten what it feels like to be a driver and  

204
00:18:15,760 --> 00:18:22,000
I carry that emotion with me and that has built 
a level of empathy in my mind for drivers. And I  

205
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:27,440
want to make sure that my team understands that's 
their life and everything we build for them has to  

206
00:18:27,440 --> 00:18:32,960
have that level of empathy. And I would say that 
was a big surprise for me. It's not just about the  

207
00:18:32,960 --> 00:18:38,000
app. Yes, there are many features in the app that 
we can talk about which are also surprising, but  

208
00:18:38,000 --> 00:18:42,880
what does a driver feel day in and day out as they 
interact with other human beings was a big one.

209
00:18:43,520 --> 00:18:48,240
I love that. I want to talk about how you actually 
disseminate this culture within the product team,  

210
00:18:48,240 --> 00:18:53,520
but out of curiosity, I always wonder what 
pisses off a driver as a rider? For example,  

211
00:18:53,520 --> 00:18:58,160
do drivers like short rides or do they 
like long rides? Does it not matter?

212
00:18:58,160 --> 00:19:03,200
I think the short or long rides can be very 
personal. There are some drivers and the great  

213
00:19:03,200 --> 00:19:08,560
thing about our driver base is there's a lot of 
heterogeneity in terms of their preferences. Some  

214
00:19:08,560 --> 00:19:14,320
of them do like shot trips because it keeps them 
closer to their home, they can make a decision  

215
00:19:14,320 --> 00:19:20,720
to go back whenever they want. Sometimes we have 
incentives which if they do 20 trips, then they  

216
00:19:20,720 --> 00:19:25,440
get something more. They're able to do that. And 
some of them just like a long trip because they  

217
00:19:25,440 --> 00:19:29,280
don't want to do multiple pickups and drop-offs. 
So I think there's a lot of heterogeneity. 

218
00:19:29,280 --> 00:19:35,120
If you want a tip for what not to do to annoy 
a driver, I'll give you a couple of tips. It's  

219
00:19:35,120 --> 00:19:41,520
totally okay for you to be on the phone. We have 
to do that. Just ask them for permission to say,  

220
00:19:41,520 --> 00:19:47,120
"Are you okay if I'm on the phone?" They will 
always say yes, but it will just annoy them a  

221
00:19:47,120 --> 00:19:52,800
lot less. So that's number one thing that I've 
learned. The number two, on your way out do not  

222
00:19:52,800 --> 00:20:01,280
slam the door. It is their car. It is their final 
moment of interaction with you. Close the door  

223
00:20:01,280 --> 00:20:06,720
and do it softly. That will ensure that you 
actually get good ratings from the driver.

224
00:20:06,720 --> 00:20:09,920
These are great tips. I know you can 
check your actual rating now on the  

225
00:20:09,920 --> 00:20:15,600
Uber app as a passenger and so it's not 
5.0 for most people including myself,  

226
00:20:15,600 --> 00:20:21,920
so this is good to know what might've caused 
that. Oh, man. Okay. One other just that I want  

227
00:20:21,920 --> 00:20:28,960
to follow here is you spending so much time 
on the experience implies that that is a huge  

228
00:20:28,960 --> 00:20:35,040
lever for growth and retention and long-term 
success. A lot of people in growth and product  

229
00:20:35,040 --> 00:20:39,840
don't see it that way. They focus on what's 
a metric we can drive, what's a conversion  

230
00:20:39,840 --> 00:20:44,480
opportunity here? They're not just like, how do 
we just make this experience better? Can you just  

231
00:20:44,480 --> 00:20:50,240
talk about that insight of just why you believe 
just making that experience better so important?

232
00:20:50,240 --> 00:20:56,640
I think it's not an or, it's an and. I do 
think that obsessing over your metrics,  

233
00:20:56,640 --> 00:21:01,200
especially when it's funnel metrics and 
understanding all the points of friction,  

234
00:21:01,200 --> 00:21:07,840
numbers do tell the story. So I think you do need 
to have the experience points whether they are  

235
00:21:07,840 --> 00:21:13,120
observed anecdotally or they come through some 
other means as well as understanding the points  

236
00:21:13,120 --> 00:21:18,480
of friction because of drop off in your conversion 
funnel, they're very important. But you can't just  

237
00:21:18,480 --> 00:21:23,920
have that. Because if... I mean, you're talking 
about end users, if it becomes just a mathematical  

238
00:21:23,920 --> 00:21:29,680
exercise, I don't think that is enough, because 
as I mentioned, what they're actually feeling  

239
00:21:29,680 --> 00:21:35,520
in the moment is something that numbers will 
never show. And numbers will not bring the  

240
00:21:35,520 --> 00:21:41,120
level of intensity that emotions will bring.
Now the question is, do you have a culture  

241
00:21:41,120 --> 00:21:47,840
that allows coexistence of both? Does it allow 
a coexistence of you bringing emotion as well  

242
00:21:47,840 --> 00:21:53,520
as the numbers? And that's what I am trying 
to create every day. Our leadership team is  

243
00:21:53,520 --> 00:21:58,480
trying to create every day, the product team, the 
engineering team is trying to create every day.  

244
00:21:58,480 --> 00:22:04,240
I think we have done a good job of having 
a coexistence of those two in the company.

245
00:22:04,240 --> 00:22:09,440
Okay. And then, so how do you operationalize 
this and make this a part of the culture at  

246
00:22:09,440 --> 00:22:14,000
the company? Clearly, part of it is modeling it 
and just doing a lot of it yourself. What else do  

247
00:22:14,000 --> 00:22:20,720
you do to help product people build this empathy 
and dogfood as much as you do or just some extent?

248
00:22:20,720 --> 00:22:27,600
I mean I do it. Tara does it. So there is 
definitely just doing by example or teaching  

249
00:22:27,600 --> 00:22:33,120
by example. We also organize around it, because 
I think creating a little bit of an organization  

250
00:22:33,120 --> 00:22:41,360
around it just helps. We are a large company 
now and we try to assist with this by centrally  

251
00:22:41,360 --> 00:22:47,760
organizing. This means let's make sure that 
everyone understands what it means to be an  

252
00:22:47,760 --> 00:22:53,040
Uber driver, how to sign up for an Uber driver. 
Some people may be on visas and so on. So there  

253
00:22:53,040 --> 00:22:58,800
is a regulatory part of that. So we make sure that 
everyone understands how to sign up. Then we also  

254
00:22:58,800 --> 00:23:04,800
organize, every year we organize, every quarter 
we organize one week of driving and delivery.  

255
00:23:04,800 --> 00:23:09,680
And we have a little bit of a competition. So we 
have hundreds of employees who go out and drive  

256
00:23:09,680 --> 00:23:15,200
and deliver and there's a competition of who can 
do the most number of trips and who can bring in  

257
00:23:15,200 --> 00:23:21,200
the most amount of feedback in terms of things 
to improve and we have prices and so on. And  

258
00:23:21,200 --> 00:23:26,800
that's just taken off over the last, I would say 
especially the last maybe three years post-COVID  

259
00:23:26,800 --> 00:23:31,200
because during COVID I think it was a little 
bit harder for us to gather everyone together. 

260
00:23:31,200 --> 00:23:37,280
And then the last thing I'll say is, what do you 
do with all of that feedback? Because that's when  

261
00:23:37,280 --> 00:23:43,280
the "boring" part starts. Now you're gathering all 
these documents, you're taking all those issues,  

262
00:23:43,280 --> 00:23:46,960
you're putting them in your Jira tracking 
or whatever tracker you may be using and  

263
00:23:46,960 --> 00:23:52,400
you're fixing them. So what we have done 
is you have set a six monthly OKR. So we  

264
00:23:52,400 --> 00:23:57,680
have set an OKR that we are going to fix 
300 of these issues. Every team actually,  

265
00:23:57,680 --> 00:24:02,560
the driver team will fix 300 of these issues. 
The rider team will fix 300 of these issues,  

266
00:24:02,560 --> 00:24:08,000
and same for the Uber Eats team. Now, I don't 
really care whether it's 300 or 200 or 500.  

267
00:24:08,000 --> 00:24:12,560
The number actually doesn't matter, but the 
fact that there is a number is what matters,  

268
00:24:12,560 --> 00:24:17,360
and we have been hitting those targets 
every single half over the last two to  

269
00:24:17,360 --> 00:24:21,120
three years. So these are some of the things 
that we do to operationalize it and make sure  

270
00:24:21,120 --> 00:24:26,000
that people understand that this behavior 
is not just expected but it's also rewarded.

271
00:24:26,000 --> 00:24:31,760
I imagine what's challenging about this is there's 
also work to do that will clearly drive growth,  

272
00:24:31,760 --> 00:24:39,280
will clearly cut down support tickets, will 
help with infrastructure costs. So these OKRs,  

273
00:24:39,280 --> 00:24:42,880
there's "Just fix these things that we know 
suck. We don't know what good they'll do,  

274
00:24:42,880 --> 00:24:48,480
but we know they're not good." How do you 
balance that in resource and prioritization  

275
00:24:48,480 --> 00:24:51,760
versus all these other things on the roadmap 
that you know are going to drive a metric?

276
00:24:51,760 --> 00:24:59,200
We have a pretty good balance set of OKRs. So 
let's say one of our teams has six OKRs just  

277
00:24:59,200 --> 00:25:04,320
illustratively over the next six months. One of 
them would be ... We call them fix-its, so we sign  

278
00:25:04,320 --> 00:25:10,720
up for 300 fix-its for the next six months. In 
addition to that, we do sign up for a growth goal.  

279
00:25:10,720 --> 00:25:17,520
We sign up for a retention goal. We sign up for a 
cost savings goal. And each of them have projects  

280
00:25:17,520 --> 00:25:25,120
behind them and the executional rigor is a pretty 
big part of Uber. So for all of those projects,  

281
00:25:25,120 --> 00:25:31,360
we actually have, and I get engaged in that as 
well, we have pretty serious executional rigor. 

282
00:25:31,360 --> 00:25:38,400
Now, OKRs are not meant to be hit hundred percent. 
I think we celebrate if we hit about 75 to 80%  

283
00:25:38,400 --> 00:25:44,160
because you do want to set stretch targets, 
and then every half we do planning. And we will  

284
00:25:44,160 --> 00:25:51,040
allocate resources between all of those OKRs. So 
fix-its, for example, don't get all the resources,  

285
00:25:51,040 --> 00:25:56,320
but they also don't get zero resources, which 
may have been the case if we had not set a  

286
00:25:56,320 --> 00:26:02,320
culture which celebrated this and allocated 
resources towards this and rewarded this.

287
00:26:02,320 --> 00:26:08,800
Awesome. Okay. Clearly, an important 
ingredient here is the CO and C-suite  

288
00:26:08,800 --> 00:26:14,480
on down values of this as something we will 
invest in and we'll trade off all focus on  

289
00:26:14,480 --> 00:26:20,080
growth for this because we believe this is 
going to help us grow and win long term.

290
00:26:20,080 --> 00:26:22,400
Absolutely, absolutely.

291
00:26:22,400 --> 00:26:27,680
Some people hearing this just as a final 
question along this area are going to feel like,  

292
00:26:27,680 --> 00:26:32,720
"Okay, Uber so easy to dogfood. Of course, I 
order Uber Eats every day. I'll go and ride.  

293
00:26:32,720 --> 00:26:39,680
So good. This is what a dream. I'm dogfooding like 
crazy." But a lot of people work at Oracle and  

294
00:26:40,960 --> 00:26:46,720
Snowflake and I don't know, Fivetran, all these 
companies where it's much less, non-consumer  

295
00:26:46,720 --> 00:26:51,760
product essentially where it's more difficult 
to dogfood. Just any advice for folks that want  

296
00:26:51,760 --> 00:26:57,840
to create a culture of dogfooding and up their 
dogfood game at a product that isn't consumering.

297
00:26:57,840 --> 00:27:02,480
So first of all, we thought the same when we 
thought about the driver app as well because  

298
00:27:02,480 --> 00:27:07,920
it was a little bit distant for people. Now, I 
would say while it is more difficult than just  

299
00:27:07,920 --> 00:27:13,840
ordering food and taking a ride, it is not as 
difficult as perhaps some of the other products  

300
00:27:13,840 --> 00:27:18,720
that you mentioned. But I do think that you just 
stretch that even further. We do have a product  

301
00:27:18,720 --> 00:27:25,200
we call Uber for Business where it's a business 
admin using it. We do have our merchant product.  

302
00:27:25,200 --> 00:27:31,280
So Uber Eats is actually three sides of the 
marketplace. The eater, the consumer, the courier  

303
00:27:31,280 --> 00:27:36,560
who's bringing your food and there's a restaurant.
Now, how do I dogfood the restaurant product, for  

304
00:27:36,560 --> 00:27:42,720
example. So these questions are very, very valid. 
So my guidance would be, and what I try to do is  

305
00:27:42,720 --> 00:27:50,720
try to get as close to that customer as possible. 
So in the case of a merchant, we go spend time at  

306
00:27:50,720 --> 00:27:59,600
restaurants. I'll give you a latest one. So we 
have a cafe here at Uber on campus. We also have  

307
00:27:59,600 --> 00:28:07,920
a barista. So we enable the barista to be an Uber 
Eats restaurant, and they have an Uber Eats tablet  

308
00:28:07,920 --> 00:28:13,600
and I can actually order from that barista. So 
now you're dogfooding being an eater, you're  

309
00:28:13,600 --> 00:28:20,080
dogfooding being a courier and you can dogfood 
being a merchant. So some of my product team,  

310
00:28:20,080 --> 00:28:24,400
they actually will go to the barista, they'll 
stand behind the counter and they'll experience  

311
00:28:24,400 --> 00:28:29,680
what it feels like for these orders to come in.
We have very close relationships with our big  

312
00:28:29,680 --> 00:28:36,480
customers such as McDonald's or Domino's and 
all of them. We also have a lot of small-medium  

313
00:28:36,480 --> 00:28:43,440
business restaurants and we have relationships 
with them which allows us to go and spend days  

314
00:28:43,440 --> 00:28:49,520
with them so that we can observe what life is like 
behind the counter for a restaurant worker, for a  

315
00:28:49,520 --> 00:28:56,320
kitchen worker, how does our product show up, and 
we learn a lot of stuff, Lenny. And I would ask  

316
00:28:56,320 --> 00:29:01,200
everyone who's listening, irrespective of the 
product that they're working on, go to the nth  

317
00:29:01,200 --> 00:29:05,760
degree of how much you can stretch. And if it's 
really an IT admin at your customer who's using  

318
00:29:05,760 --> 00:29:12,400
your product, I would do two things. A, go to that 
IT admin and sit next to them and observe them  

319
00:29:12,400 --> 00:29:19,040
using the product. B, set up what we call test 
accounts and try to pretend to be an IT admin and  

320
00:29:19,040 --> 00:29:24,880
set up that account. I went through our merchant 
setup flow, which I can just do by setting up a  

321
00:29:24,880 --> 00:29:30,480
test account and I learned so many things of all 
the points of friction that we are putting in that  

322
00:29:30,480 --> 00:29:35,680
flow. So I think there is still a lot that you 
can do even if you do not have a consumer product.

323
00:29:35,680 --> 00:29:42,000
Awesome. So the advice there is just find a way, 
get as close as you can. You may not be able to  

324
00:29:42,000 --> 00:29:46,480
ride an Uber, drive an Uber car, get an Uber 
ride, but there's some way you can get really  

325
00:29:46,480 --> 00:29:52,000
close. You may not be exactly do the thing. 
Awesome. Okay. I'm going to go in a different  

326
00:29:52,000 --> 00:29:55,840
direction and there's another theme that came 
up again and again when I was asking people  

327
00:29:55,840 --> 00:30:01,280
about you and what you're amazing at. And a 
motto came up again and again it was ship,  

328
00:30:01,280 --> 00:30:07,920
ship, ship. Talk about that. Why is this 
motto, this way of working so important  

329
00:30:07,920 --> 00:30:11,680
to you? Why is it something you try to 
encourage everyone to always think about?

330
00:30:11,680 --> 00:30:16,320
I think it's actually a natural extension of 
what we just talked about. If we are going to  

331
00:30:16,320 --> 00:30:22,480
go dogfood and experience this pain and you're 
going to document it, what's next? You have to  

332
00:30:22,480 --> 00:30:29,440
ship this. I'm a big believer in you don't ship 
documents, you don't ship brainstorming meetings,  

333
00:30:29,440 --> 00:30:35,440
you don't even ship designs in a Figma. What you 
ship is code in your product. That is the only  

334
00:30:35,440 --> 00:30:41,120
thing that actually ultimately has impact 
on the end user. So as I mentioned before,  

335
00:30:41,120 --> 00:30:47,040
I develop a sense of impatience. It's a 
positive impatience if you will, that,  

336
00:30:47,040 --> 00:30:52,880
"Okay, I just observed a problem for our 
riders or for our drivers. They have to  

337
00:30:52,880 --> 00:30:57,120
get a solution to that as soon as possible." 
And for that, you have to ship, ship, ship. 

338
00:30:57,120 --> 00:31:02,880
Now, you could interpret ship, ship, ship to 
be just mindlessly shipping. No, this is not  

339
00:31:02,880 --> 00:31:07,840
about mindlessly shipping, but once you know that 
you're working on something that is important,  

340
00:31:07,840 --> 00:31:12,240
that is solving a problem, it could be a big 
feature or a small feature, then you have to  

341
00:31:12,240 --> 00:31:18,480
cut down the cycle time. My biggest enemy is 
the cycle time of we know it is a good thing  

342
00:31:18,480 --> 00:31:24,640
all the way to our users seeing it, you have to 
minimize that time. So that's why ship, ship, ship  

343
00:31:24,640 --> 00:31:30,800
has become such a motto for me and we try to do a 
lot of things internally operationally for us to  

344
00:31:30,800 --> 00:31:36,480
enable that. And I'll say we still are not there. 
In my opinion, I think we can still be faster,  

345
00:31:36,480 --> 00:31:42,720
we can still cut a lot of that cycle time, but we 
are on a constant quest to get as good as we can.

346
00:31:42,720 --> 00:31:46,960
What does this look like in practice other 
than just reminding people, "Ship, ship,  

347
00:31:46,960 --> 00:31:51,120
ship. Ship, ship, ship." Just repeating this 
mantra. How do you help people ship faster,  

348
00:31:51,120 --> 00:31:53,840
to your point, not just 
work all night and all day,  

349
00:31:55,520 --> 00:31:59,120
staying long hours, just what are some 
ways to actually operationalize this?

350
00:31:59,120 --> 00:32:06,960
I think it stems from the cutting down cycle time, 
which is the time it takes to make decisions. I  

351
00:32:06,960 --> 00:32:12,320
realized that a lot of the time is not... I 
mean, all the time that you spend documenting  

352
00:32:12,320 --> 00:32:18,240
the requirements or designing the product 
or actually writing code is time really,  

353
00:32:18,240 --> 00:32:24,960
really well spent. All the time that is 
spent in between those activities to align,  

354
00:32:24,960 --> 00:32:30,960
to discuss a decision, to not make up your 
mind, then have a meeting the next week,  

355
00:32:30,960 --> 00:32:36,000
"Oh, let's regroup two weeks from now." 
That happens in our companies a lot.  

356
00:32:36,000 --> 00:32:43,680
The question is, how do you cut that down? And for 
that what we do is we have product reviews and as  

357
00:32:43,680 --> 00:32:50,080
much as possible we try to come out with decisions 
in those product reviews. And you have to operate  

358
00:32:50,080 --> 00:32:56,080
in a one-way door versus two-way door concept.
If something is a two-way door, you have to  

359
00:32:56,080 --> 00:33:01,360
be able to make the call quickly and you want 
to make a good call, but if you get it wrong,  

360
00:33:01,360 --> 00:33:06,880
it's okay, we can turn it back. If it is a 
one-way door, if it's a massive launch, sure,  

361
00:33:06,880 --> 00:33:11,440
it's okay for it to take some deliberation. 
Maybe it even goes through the C-suite and  

362
00:33:11,440 --> 00:33:17,200
we have a discussion, but my guidance to my 
team is cut down the decision-making that has  

363
00:33:17,200 --> 00:33:22,320
to happen or to cut down the time required for 
the decision-making between those various steps.

364
00:33:22,320 --> 00:33:27,040
A few things I heard that you do that you didn't 
mention that I think helped with this, one is that  

365
00:33:27,040 --> 00:33:31,600
there was a period where you ran daily stand-ups 
with cross-functional teams during COVID just to  

366
00:33:31,600 --> 00:33:36,320
keep things moving. There's another story I heard 
where you wrote a 15-page PRD over the weekend to  

367
00:33:36,320 --> 00:33:42,640
unblock a stall team. It feels like these are ... 
look for opportunities to unblock essentially.

368
00:33:42,640 --> 00:33:48,560
Well, I want that to be an exception rather 
than the rule, but yes, I want to be able to  

369
00:33:48,560 --> 00:33:52,720
step in or I want all our leaders to be able 
to step in when needed. I think you have to  

370
00:33:52,720 --> 00:33:58,960
be hands-on. You have to be hands-on when needed. 
Those two examples, we were coming out of COVID,  

371
00:33:58,960 --> 00:34:05,920
we had a massive shortage of drivers on our 
platform and we were talking about growth  

372
00:34:05,920 --> 00:34:13,040
earlier and we had clear goals on how we grow the 
number of drivers on our platform all the way from  

373
00:34:13,040 --> 00:34:19,120
getting new drivers in and improving the funnel 
as well as regaining existing drivers. And Lenny,  

374
00:34:19,120 --> 00:34:24,480
there was no shortage of the number of ideas, but 
again, there was a problem with cycle time. So  

375
00:34:24,480 --> 00:34:30,080
I said, "Great, our cycle time is going to be 24 
hours." And so I think there was a period of about  

376
00:34:30,080 --> 00:34:36,560
six months when we did do daily stand-ups and 
they were extremely helpful to unblock the teams  

377
00:34:36,560 --> 00:34:42,480
on making certain decisions and we shipped a lot. 
And I think it took us about nine to 12 months,  

378
00:34:42,480 --> 00:34:46,880
but we were able to come out the other 
side having a great number of drivers. 

379
00:34:46,880 --> 00:34:52,400
And the great thing is that what we did in 
our driver and courier funnel at that time is  

380
00:34:52,400 --> 00:34:58,400
still paying off because the number of drivers 
and couriers continues to grow and now we are  

381
00:34:58,400 --> 00:35:03,920
worldwide at about an eight million number. 
And we were probably close to half of that  

382
00:35:04,960 --> 00:35:09,280
when we were just out of COVID. So that's 
an example of where daily standards help,  

383
00:35:09,280 --> 00:35:15,920
I try to minimize that. The PRD exam, yes, 
I did write a PRD. It was a 15-page PRD. We  

384
00:35:15,920 --> 00:35:23,520
were working on a pretty big concept and it was a 
risky concept. And it was driver facing and that's  

385
00:35:23,520 --> 00:35:31,840
always high stakes. And by this time, we have had 
about 20 conversations and brainstorm meetings and  

386
00:35:31,840 --> 00:35:36,720
documents that had been written with the best 
intentions, but thing that was not becoming  

387
00:35:36,720 --> 00:35:41,600
clear is, hey, what should we actually ship?
Because there were a lot of good ideas and not  

388
00:35:41,600 --> 00:35:47,600
so good ideas, but no one was actually putting it 
all together to say, "This is what we're going to  

389
00:35:47,600 --> 00:35:53,600
ship." So it was one Sunday night and I literally, 
it took me two hours and I just wrote down,  

390
00:35:53,600 --> 00:35:57,760
I'm like, "Guys, this is my stake in the ground. 
We can completely change it, but this is the  

391
00:35:57,760 --> 00:36:03,040
product we will ship. Agree or disagree." Now, the 
product that we eventually shipped was at least  

392
00:36:03,040 --> 00:36:10,320
50% different than what I had written down, but it 
just catalyzed us getting to that endpoint. Now,  

393
00:36:10,320 --> 00:36:14,960
if I were to do that every single day or every 
single week, then I would say there's a problem.

394
00:36:14,960 --> 00:36:18,640
Yeah, you wouldn't have time 
to deliver food and give rides.

395
00:36:18,640 --> 00:36:22,480
That is exactly right. Or I would not 
have time to do hiring or I would not  

396
00:36:22,480 --> 00:36:27,440
have time to do performance reviews and 
so on. But once in a while, I think it's  

397
00:36:27,440 --> 00:36:32,960
totally fine for product leaders to step in, 
especially if you're trying to remove ambiguity  

398
00:36:32,960 --> 00:36:37,600
and you're trying to just speed decisions 
up. It's okay to step in and be hands-on.

399
00:36:37,600 --> 00:36:43,120
Another tactic that I heard that I want 
to ask you about, someone anonymously  

400
00:36:43,120 --> 00:36:47,840
said that you ask for live demos. And here's 
the question, he always insist on doing live  

401
00:36:47,840 --> 00:36:53,600
demos that make everyone nervous when 
they present. The question is, why?

402
00:36:53,600 --> 00:37:00,560
So I think they may be talking about when we 
do product announcements. So when we do product  

403
00:37:00,560 --> 00:37:09,120
announcements, externally, on stage, et cetera, 
I do insist on actually live demoing the product.  

404
00:37:09,120 --> 00:37:16,800
Part of this comes from, I grew up as a product 
manager back in the day in the 2000s at Palm.  

405
00:37:16,800 --> 00:37:22,880
Palm where the Palm Pilot. Palm was cut from the 
Apple clock. There were a lot of ex-Apple people  

406
00:37:22,880 --> 00:37:28,320
there and we were in the consumer electronics 
business. And every single year the way you would  

407
00:37:28,320 --> 00:37:33,600
announce your product is you would get up on stage 
and you show the product working. And leading  

408
00:37:33,600 --> 00:37:40,080
up to that moment was a lot of massive amount of 
work to make sure that it actually works on stage. 

409
00:37:40,080 --> 00:37:44,800
Now, I will say there's an internal 
reason and an external reason to do this.  

410
00:37:44,800 --> 00:37:53,520
The external reason to do this is you have 
to tell a story. One of my other beliefs is,  

411
00:37:53,520 --> 00:37:59,520
which I may not have shared before, is no one 
actually really cares about the feature that  

412
00:37:59,520 --> 00:38:05,280
you want to talk about. People are way too 
busy. You are obsessed about your products,  

413
00:38:05,280 --> 00:38:11,200
you, your products are your life, but for your 
end users, your products are maybe 10 minutes of  

414
00:38:11,200 --> 00:38:18,560
their life once a week. So their life does not 
center around your products. They don't care. 

415
00:38:18,560 --> 00:38:24,000
How do you make them care? You have to tell 
a story and that story comes from actually  

416
00:38:24,000 --> 00:38:29,840
showing the product in action rather than a lot of 
slideware and pictures. So that is my belief that  

417
00:38:29,840 --> 00:38:34,640
I don't want to have hubris about my own product. 
I need to be able to tell a story about how an end  

418
00:38:34,640 --> 00:38:40,480
user will actually get value out of that. That's 
my external reason for why I insist on live demos. 

419
00:38:40,480 --> 00:38:47,280
My internal reasons for why I insist on 
a live demo is while it is a lot of work,  

420
00:38:47,280 --> 00:38:55,120
I think it creates a certain level of rigor ahead 
of time before the product is ready to launch.  

421
00:38:55,120 --> 00:39:02,240
Because if it is going up on stage, it has to 
work. And two, you may ask the same person who  

422
00:39:02,240 --> 00:39:07,760
asked you this. It creates such a sense of pride 
amongst the product team and the engineering team  

423
00:39:07,760 --> 00:39:14,880
to actually see their product live on stage 
and now it's on video and it'll stay forever,  

424
00:39:14,880 --> 00:39:19,520
to see the product that they put their 
blood and tears into actually working.  

425
00:39:19,520 --> 00:39:23,440
I think that's a huge moment of pride and I 
take it as personal responsibility to make  

426
00:39:23,440 --> 00:39:28,560
sure that I can help bring that moment. But 
yes, leading up to that is a lot of work.

