494
00:45:30,160 --> 00:45:36,240
What has not changed in those 24 years 
is you having to understand what your  

495
00:45:36,240 --> 00:45:40,800
end users want. And I know that's kind of 
the cliché of product management. "Yes,  

496
00:45:40,800 --> 00:45:46,400
of course I have to understand what my end user 
wants." I think it is harder than we think. I  

497
00:45:46,400 --> 00:45:52,720
think it takes more than we typically do to 
actually really get your finger on the pulse  

498
00:45:52,720 --> 00:45:58,400
of what your end user feels. And I think that 
that has stayed constant. I think that is the  

499
00:45:58,400 --> 00:46:04,800
holy grail, not just to understand one 
archetype of an end user. At Uber here,  

500
00:46:04,800 --> 00:46:11,440
not only are we operational in 75 different 
countries, even in a single country like the US,  

501
00:46:11,440 --> 00:46:18,240
we have different kinds of end users, whether it's 
demographics, whether it is socioeconomic status,  

502
00:46:18,240 --> 00:46:24,080
and for us to internalize what do end users 
want, AI will definitely speed it up, but for  

503
00:46:24,080 --> 00:46:30,000
a product manager, it is going to stay constant.
The one thing I do think product managers need to  

504
00:46:30,000 --> 00:46:38,400
be aware of is the importance of knowledge 
